  "texts": [
    "To this end, we leverage a hypergraph neural network with skip connection skills to model such complex interactions.Let 𝑯 ∈ {0, 1} | V | × | E | denote whether a node is present in a given hyperedge.",
    "For example, 𝑯 𝑢𝑘 = 1 means the 𝑢-th user of V is the member of the 𝑘-th environment (hyperedge), and 𝑯 𝑢𝑘 = 0 for the opposite.",
    "The degree of 𝑘-th hyperedge is defined as 𝑑 𝑒 𝑘 = 𝑢 ∈ V 𝑼 𝑢 𝑯 𝑢𝑘, leading to a diagonal hyperedge degree matrix as𝑫 𝑒 = 𝑫 𝒊𝒂𝒈(𝑑 𝑒 1, • • •, 𝑑 𝑒 | E |) ∈ R | E | × | E |.",
    "The node degree matrix can be also given similarly like𝑫 𝑣 = 𝑫 𝒊𝒂𝒈(𝑑 𝑣 1, • • •, 𝑑 𝑣 | V |) ∈ R | V | × | V | where 𝑑 𝑣 𝑘 = 𝑘 ∈ E ℎ 𝑾 𝑘 𝑯 𝑢𝑘.Then the hypergraph Laplacian matrix 5 For privacy concerns, we present a fake name here.can be defined as follows:𝚫 = 𝑰 -𝑫 𝑣 -1 2 𝑼 𝑯𝑾 𝑫 𝑒 -1 𝑯 T 𝑼 𝑫 𝑣 -1 2(4)We are particularly interested in the second item of the above equation, which is (𝑫 𝑣) -1 2 𝑼 𝑯𝑾 (𝑫 𝑒) -1 𝑯 T 𝑼 (𝑫 𝑣) -1 2, because this matrix reflects that the information flows from nodes to hyperedges and then from hyperedges to nodes.",
    "This is very consistent with our observations in the sociological area, which indicates the interaction between users and their environments."
